OpenIdiom — Headless Knowledge Base CLI with AI Integration

 Context

 Obsidian is a powerful knowledge management tool, but it's closed-source, GUI-bound, and lacks native AI integration. Existing open-source alternatives (Logseq, Joplin) all focus on
 building another GUI editor — solving the wrong problem. The real value in a Markdown knowledge base isn't the editor (VS Code, Neovim, and Obsidian itself already exist), it's the
 graph intelligence and AI layer on top of plain files.

 OpenIdiom is a Rust CLI tool that treats a folder of Markdown files as a knowledge base. It indexes wikilinks, tags, and frontmatter; exposes a query interface; and provides an AI layer
  for semantic search, summarization, and link discovery. It's editor-agnostic, local-first, and designed to integrate with shell workflows and AI assistants (including Claude Code).

 Target users: Developers, writers, and knowledge workers who already have an editor they like and want programmable intelligence over their notes.

